<section class="guideSection" id="tent-size">
  <h2>Grow Tent Size: 2x2 vs 2x4 vs 3x3 vs 4x4</h2>

  <p>
    Grow tent size should be chosen around the crop, the light footprint, and the amount of airflow you can realistically manage.
  </p>

  <p>
    A tent that is too small becomes crowded quickly. A tent that is too large can waste light, hold excess humidity, and require more ventilation than a beginner expects.
  </p>

  <h3>2x2 Grow Tent</h3>

  <p>
    A 2x2 grow tent is the easiest size to fit into a small room or apartment. It works well for herbs, lettuce, microgreens, a small seedling setup, or one compact crop zone.
  </p>

  <p>
    The main limitation is that everything is tight: lights, fans, trays, containers, and plant canopy all compete for space.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> herbs, greens, microgreens, small seedling batches, and compact indoor setups.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Usually avoid for:</strong> full-size tomatoes, large pepper plants, or anything that needs serious vertical and horizontal space.
  </p>

  <h3>2x4 Grow Tent</h3>

  <p>
    A 2x4 grow tent is usually the best default size for indoor vegetable gardening because it matches seed trays and rectangular grow-light footprints so well.
  </p>

  <p>
    It gives more working room than a 2x2 without becoming as demanding as a 4x4.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> seed-starting trays, herbs, leafy greens, peppers, compact tomatoes, and mixed indoor vegetable setups.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Watch out for:</strong> poor airflow at one end of the tent if circulation is weak.
  </p>

  <h3>3x3 Grow Tent</h3>

  <p>
    A 3x3 grow tent gives more canopy width than a 2x4 and can feel more flexible for larger plants.
  </p>

  <p>
    This size works well when you want more space around containers and foliage but do not want to jump to a full 4x4 setup.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> larger indoor vegetable projects, peppers, compact tomatoes, and gardeners who want more plant spacing.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Watch out for:</strong> light coverage. Make sure your grow light actually covers the square footprint well.
  </p>

  <h3>4x4 Grow Tent</h3>

  <p>
    A 4x4 grow tent is a serious indoor growing space. It can hold more plants and stronger lights, but it also becomes harder to manage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Heat, humidity, watering, ventilation, and plant access all become more important as the tent gets larger.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> experienced indoor gardeners, larger vegetable projects, and strong light/ventilation systems.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Watch out for:</strong> buying the tent before understanding the light, fan, and room requirements.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>Best Default Size</h2>

    <p>
      For most indoor vegetable gardeners, a sturdy 2x4 grow tent is the best starting point. It fits trays efficiently, works with common LED light layouts, and gives more breathing room than a 2x2 without becoming as demanding as a 4x4.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="height-clearance">
  <h2>Grow Tent Height and Plant Clearance</h2>

  <p>
    The listed height of a grow tent is not the same as the usable plant height.
  </p>

  <p>
    Usable height is what remains after you subtract the container, saucer, plant, grow light, hangers, fan, ducting, and safe light distance.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>The Practical Height Rule</h2>

    <p>
      The usable height of a grow tent is not the listed height. It is the space left after the pot, plant, light, hangers, and airflow equipment are all inside.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Seedlings Need Less Height</h3>

  <p>
    Seedlings, microgreens, and young herbs do not need a tall grow tent. They need even light, manageable humidity, and enough room to raise or lower the light.
  </p>

  <p>
    A short propagation tent or compact 2x2 can work well if the crop will move outdoors or into another setup before it gets large.
  </p>

  <h3>Peppers Need More Room Than They Seem</h3>

  <p>
    Pepper plants are shorter than tomatoes, but they still need container depth, canopy space, and airflow around the leaves.
  </p>

  <p>
    A tent that feels roomy for seedlings can become crowded once peppers move into larger pots.
  </p>

  <h3>Tomatoes Are a Height Problem</h3>

  <p>
    Tomatoes are one of the easiest crops to underestimate indoors.
  </p>

  <p>
    Even compact tomatoes need space for pots, pruning, supports, lights, and airflow. Full-size indeterminate tomatoes are usually a poor fit for small tents unless you are intentionally using aggressive pruning and support.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most indoor vegetable gardeners, compact or dwarf tomato varieties make far more sense than trying to force full-size garden tomatoes into a short tent.
  </p>

  <h3>Lights Need Clearance Too</h3>

  <p>
    Grow lights take up physical space and often need distance from the plant canopy.
  </p>

  <p>
    If the tent is too short, plants can grow into the light before they are mature. This creates stress, heat issues, and uneven growth.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    Tent height and light distance work together. For lighting guidance, see <a href="/guides/best-grow-lights-for-seedlings/">best grow lights for seedlings</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="ventilation">
  <h2>Ventilation, Fans, and Airflow</h2>

  <p>
    A grow tent without airflow quickly becomes a humidity box.
  </p>

  <p>
    Lights add heat. Plants release moisture. Wet trays and containers raise humidity. Without ventilation, the tent can become warm, damp, and stagnant.
  </p>

  <p>
    Airflow is not optional if the tent will run for more than short seed-starting sessions.
  </p>

  <h3>Exhaust Removes Heat and Humidity</h3>

  <p>
    Exhaust fans move warm, humid air out of the tent and pull fresher room air in through intake openings.
  </p>

  <p>
    This matters more as the tent gets larger, lights get stronger, and plants grow denser.
  </p>

  <h3>Circulation Fans Move Air Inside the Tent</h3>

  <p>
    Internal circulation fans prevent still pockets of air around leaves and trays.
  </p>

  <p>
    For seedlings, the airflow should be gentle. For larger plants, the goal is steady air movement through the canopy without blasting one plant constantly.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    For small indoor starts, see <a href="/guides/best-fan-for-seedlings-indoors/">best fan for seedlings indoors</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>Passive Intake Still Needs a Path</h3>

  <p>
    Many grow tents use passive intake vents near the bottom. These only work well if air can actually enter the tent and move through the growing area.
  </p>

  <p>
    Do not block every intake with trays, storage bins, or a wall pressed tightly against the tent.
  </p>

  <h3>Ventilation Needs Increase With Tent Size</h3>

  <p>
    A 2x2 herb tent and a 4x4 mature vegetable tent do not need the same airflow plan.
  </p>

  <p>
    Larger tents, stronger lights, and bigger plants require more serious ventilation because heat and humidity build faster.
  </p>

  <h3>Airflow Should Match the Crop Stage</h3>

  <p>
    Seedlings need gentle circulation. Mature peppers and tomatoes need enough air movement to prevent stagnant foliage and humidity pockets.
  </p>

  <p>
    As plants grow, reassess fan placement and ventilation instead of leaving the setup exactly as it was during seed starting.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="grow-lights">
  <h2>Grow Lights and Tent Footprint</h2>

  <p>
    A grow tent is only as useful as the light inside it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Reflective walls help distribute light, but they do not turn an undersized light into a full-tent light source.
  </p>

  <p>
    The tent footprint and light footprint should be chosen together.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Tent Setup</th>
          <th>Light Fit</th>
          <th>Risk if Mismatched</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Small tent with strong light</strong></td>
          <td>Can work if dimmable and ventilated</td>
          <td>Heat, leaf stress, and limited height margin.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Large tent with weak light</strong></td>
          <td>Usually inefficient</td>
          <td>Leggy growth and wasted tent space.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>2x4 tent with matching rectangular light</strong></td>
          <td>Often efficient</td>
          <td>Still needs good end-to-end airflow.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>3x3 tent with square light footprint</strong></td>
          <td>Good fit when properly matched</td>
          <td>Uneven corners if light coverage is poor.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Seedling tent</strong></td>
          <td>Lower intensity may be enough</td>
          <td>Too much light/heat in shallow space.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Do Not Buy the Tent First and Hope the Light Fits</h3>

  <p>
    The tent and light should be planned as one system.
  </p>

  <p>
    A 4x4 tent sounds spacious, but it is not useful if the grow light only covers a small area in the center.
  </p>

  <h3>Seedlings Need Different Light Than Fruiting Vegetables</h3>

  <p>
    Seedlings need strong enough light to prevent stretching, but they do not need the same intensity as mature fruiting peppers or tomatoes.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you plan to use the tent for both seed starting and mature plants, choose lights that can be adjusted in height or intensity.
  </p>

  <h3>Reflective Walls Help, But They Are Not Magic</h3>

  <p>
    A reflective tent interior improves light efficiency, especially around the edges of the canopy.
  </p>

  <p>
    But reflective lining cannot compensate for poor light choice, weak coverage, or plants that are too far from the fixture.
  </p>

  <h3>Light Heat Affects Tent Climate</h3>

  <p>
    Even efficient LED grow lights add heat inside a tent.
  </p>

  <p>
    The stronger the light and the smaller the tent, the more attention you need to pay to exhaust, circulation, and canopy temperature.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="humidity-heat">
  <h2>Humidity, Heat, and Watering Inside a Grow Tent</h2>

  <p>
    One of the biggest advantages of a grow tent is environmental control. One of the biggest risks is creating an environment that is too warm, too humid, or too wet.
  </p>

  <p>
    Grow tents naturally hold more humidity than an open room because the walls slow air exchange and the plants continuously release moisture.
  </p>

  <p>
    That can be beneficial for young seedlings, but it can also create problems if airflow and watering are not managed properly.
  </p>

  <h3>Seed Trays Raise Humidity Quickly</h3>

  <p>
    A few trays of seedlings can release surprising amounts of moisture into a small tent.
  </p>

  <p>
    Germination domes, freshly watered trays, and dense foliage all contribute to higher humidity levels.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is one reason why a small circulation fan is often helpful even in seed-starting tents.
  </p>

  <h3>Warm, Wet Conditions Create Pest Problems</h3>

  <p>
    Fungus gnats thrive in moist growing media and often become more noticeable in enclosed indoor growing spaces.
  </p>

  <p>
    A tent does not cause fungus gnats, but it can create ideal conditions if trays stay constantly wet.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    If fungus gnats become a recurring issue, see <a href="/guides/best-beneficial-nematodes-for-fungus-gnats/">best beneficial nematodes for fungus gnats</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>Heat Mats Can Overdo It</h3>

  <p>
    Heat mats are extremely useful during germination, but gardeners sometimes leave them running longer than necessary.
  </p>

  <p>
    Inside a tent, a heat mat, grow light, and enclosed environment can combine to create warmer conditions than expected.
  </p>

  <p>
    Once seeds have germinated, reassess whether bottom heat is still helping or simply adding unnecessary warmth.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    For more guidance, see <a href="/guides/best-heat-mat-for-seedlings/">best heat mat for seedlings</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>Watering Access Matters</h3>

  <p>
    A tent that is difficult to reach often leads to inconsistent watering.
  </p>

  <p>
    Make sure you can comfortably reach every tray and container without moving half the setup every time you water.
  </p>

  <p>
    This becomes increasingly important as plants get larger and the tent fills out.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>The Humidity Rule</h2>

    <p>
      Most indoor grow-tent problems start with a combination of excess moisture and insufficient airflow. If plants look stressed, always evaluate watering and ventilation before assuming the light is the problem.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="build-quality">
  <h2>Frame Strength, Zippers, Canvas, and Light Leaks</h2>

  <p>
    Many grow tents look similar in photos, but build quality becomes obvious after months of opening zippers, adjusting lights, moving plants, and running ventilation equipment.
  </p>

  <p>
    A grow tent is not just fabric. It is a structure that must support lights, fans, ducting, filters, and repeated use.
  </p>

  <h3>Frame Strength Matters More Than Many Buyers Expect</h3>

  <p>
    Lights, fans, filters, and hanging equipment place weight on the tent frame.
  </p>

  <p>
    Weak poles or connectors may not be a problem on day one, but they become more noticeable as equipment is added.
  </p>

  <p>
    For larger tents, stronger frame construction is worth paying for.
  </p>

  <h3>Zippers Get Used Constantly</h3>

  <p>
    Every watering, pruning session, inspection, harvest, and adjustment usually involves opening the tent.
  </p>

  <p>
    Smooth, durable zippers are one of the easiest quality differences to notice during long-term use.
  </p>

  <h3>Canvas Thickness Helps Durability</h3>

  <p>
    Heavier canvas generally resists wear better and can reduce light leakage.
  </p>

  <p>
    The goal is not simply the thickest material available, but a tent that feels durable and maintains its shape under normal use.
  </p>

  <h3>Reflective Interior Matters</h3>

  <p>
    Reflective lining helps redirect light back toward the canopy and improve overall light efficiency.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most quality grow tents now include reflective interiors, but coverage quality and construction can still vary.
  </p>

  <h3>Light Leaks Usually Matter Less Than Airflow</h3>

  <p>
    Many buyers focus heavily on light leaks, but for vegetable gardeners, airflow, tent size, and lighting quality usually have a bigger impact on plant performance.
  </p>

  <p>
    Minor leaks are generally less important than poor ventilation or a badly matched grow light.
  </p>

  <h3>Useful Features Worth Paying For</h3>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>strong frame construction</li>
    <li>quality zippers</li>
    <li>multiple ventilation ports</li>
    <li>removable waterproof floor tray</li>
    <li>good reflective lining</li>
    <li>easy cable-management access</li>
    <li>sufficient hanging support for lights and fans</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These features affect daily usability far more than marketing claims about extreme reflectivity or oversized viewing windows.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="kits-vs-separate">
  <h2>Grow Tent Kits vs Buying Components Separately</h2>

  <p>
    One of the first decisions indoor gardeners face is whether to buy a complete grow tent kit or assemble the system piece by piece.
  </p>

  <p>
    Both approaches can work well, but they suit different types of growers.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Approach</th>
          <th>Main Advantage</th>
          <th>Main Drawback</th>
          <th>Best For</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Complete grow tent kit</strong></td>
          <td>Simple setup and fewer compatibility decisions.</td>
          <td>Less flexibility and customization.</td>
          <td>Beginners.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Build your own system</strong></td>
          <td>Choose each component individually.</td>
          <td>Requires more research.</td>
          <td>Experienced indoor gardeners.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Why Kits Are Popular</h3>

  <p>
    Kits reduce the number of decisions a beginner needs to make.
  </p>

  <p>
    The tent, light, fan, and basic accessories are usually chosen to work together, which lowers the risk of major compatibility mistakes.
  </p>

  <h3>Why Experienced Gardeners Often Buy Separately</h3>

  <p>
    Once you understand lighting, ventilation, humidity, and crop needs, it becomes easier to customize each component.
  </p>

  <p>
    This often results in a system that is better matched to your specific growing goals.
  </p>

  <h3>Which Option Is Better?</h3>

  <p>
    If this is your first grow tent, a kit is often the easiest path.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you already own lights, fans, trays, or environmental controls, building the system yourself may provide better long-term value.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="crop-fit">
  <h2>Best Grow Tent by Crop Type</h2>

  <p>
    Different crops place different demands on a grow tent.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choosing a tent based on what you actually grow is often more useful than choosing based on square footage alone.
  </p>

  <div class="scenarioGrid">
    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Seedlings</h3>

      <p>
        Seedlings benefit most from tray space, even lighting, and gentle airflow.
      </p>

      <p>
        Height is usually less important because the plants will eventually move outdoors.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Best tent:</strong> propagation tent or 2x4 grow tent.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Herbs</h3>

      <p>
        Herbs stay relatively compact and work well in smaller tents.
      </p>

      <p>
        Most gardeners do not need a huge footprint for basil, parsley, cilantro, or similar crops.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Best tent:</strong> 2x2 or 2x4 grow tent.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Lettuce and Greens</h3>

      <p>
        Greens prioritize canopy space more than height.
      </p>

      <p>
        Efficient light distribution and easy harvesting matter more than vertical clearance.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Best tent:</strong> 2x2, 2x4, or shelf-style setup.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Peppers</h3>

      <p>
        Peppers need more height, stronger lighting, and better airflow than seedlings or herbs.
      </p>

      <p>
        Container size becomes increasingly important as plants mature.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Best tent:</strong> tall 2x4 or 3x3 grow tent.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Tomatoes</h3>

      <p>
        Tomatoes are usually limited by height rather than width.
      </p>

      <p>
        Compact or dwarf varieties are far easier to manage indoors than full-size indeterminate garden tomatoes.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Best tent:</strong> tall 2x4, 3x3, or larger.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Microgreens</h3>

      <p>
        Microgreens use very little vertical space and benefit from efficient tray coverage.
      </p>

      <p>
        Lighting footprint is often more important than tent height.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Best tent:</strong> propagation tent or compact 2x2 setup.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="mistakes">
  <h2>Common Grow Tent Mistakes</h2>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Mistake</th>
          <th>Why It Causes Problems</th>
          <th>Better Approach</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Buying too large</strong></td>
          <td>Requires more light, airflow, and management.</td>
          <td>Match the tent to the crop and equipment.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Buying too short</strong></td>
          <td>Plants quickly reach the lights.</td>
          <td>Calculate usable height before buying.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Ignoring ventilation</strong></td>
          <td>Heat and humidity build rapidly.</td>
          <td>Plan airflow from the start.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Weak light for the footprint</strong></td>
          <td>Creates uneven growth and wasted space.</td>
          <td>Match light coverage to tent size.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Overcrowding plants</strong></td>
          <td>Reduces airflow and increases disease risk.</td>
          <td>Leave room for mature growth.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>No circulation fan</strong></td>
          <td>Creates stagnant air pockets.</td>
          <td>Provide gentle internal airflow.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Poor watering access</strong></td>
          <td>Maintenance becomes frustrating.</td>
          <td>Ensure every plant is easy to reach.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Assuming reflective walls solve everything</strong></td>
          <td>Reflectivity cannot replace proper lighting.</td>
          <td>Build around the light first.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Mixing incompatible crop stages</strong></td>
          <td>Seedlings and mature plants may need different light height, humidity, and airflow.</td>
          <td>Separate crop stages or choose a multi-chamber setup.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="troubleshooting">
  <h2>Troubleshooting Grow Tent Problems</h2>

  <div class="troubleshootingGrid">
    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>The Tent Gets Too Hot</h3>

      <p>
        Usually caused by inadequate exhaust, strong lighting, poor room ventilation, or excessive ambient room temperature.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> improve airflow and evaluate light output versus tent size.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Humidity Stays Too High</h3>

      <p>
        Common with dense foliage, seed trays, and weak ventilation.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> increase airflow, improve watering habits, and reduce stagnant air.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Seedlings Are Leggy</h3>

      <p>
        This is usually a lighting issue, not a tent issue.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> improve light intensity or reduce light distance.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Fungus Gnats Appear</h3>

      <p>
        Warm, moist growing media creates ideal conditions for fungus gnats.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> improve watering practices and treat larvae if necessary.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Plants Grow Into the Lights</h3>

      <p>
        The tent is too short, the plants are too tall, or the light cannot be raised further.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> use shorter crops, prune appropriately, or upgrade tent height.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>The Tent Feels Crowded</h3>

      <p>
        Most gardeners underestimate how much space mature plants actually need.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> reduce plant count or move to a larger footprint.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>The Back of the Tent Gets Neglected</h3>

      <p>
        This is an access bottleneck. If plants are hard to reach, they are less likely to be watered, pruned, inspected, or harvested on time.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> reduce plant count, rotate containers, improve door access, or choose a shallower tent layout next time.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="final-recommendation">
  <h2>Final Buying Recommendation</h2>

  <p>
    For most indoor vegetable gardeners, a sturdy 2x4 grow tent is the best starting point because it fits seed trays efficiently, works with common LED grow-light footprints, provides useful height, and offers more flexibility than a compact 2x2 tent.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choose a 2x2 tent for herbs, greens, and very small indoor setups. Choose a 3x3 if you want more canopy space around mature plants. Choose a 4x4 only if you are prepared to manage stronger lighting, more airflow, higher humidity loads, and a larger indoor footprint.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>Before You Buy, Check These Five Bottlenecks</h2>

    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Light footprint:</strong> does the light actually cover the tent?</li>
      <li><strong>Usable height:</strong> have you accounted for pots, plants, lights, hangers, and fans?</li>
      <li><strong>Ventilation:</strong> can you remove heat and humidity from the tent and the room?</li>
      <li><strong>Access:</strong> can you water, prune, inspect, and harvest every plant easily?</li>
      <li><strong>Crop stage:</strong> are seedlings and mature plants asking for the same environment?</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The best grow tent is not the biggest one available. It is the tent that fits your crops, your lights, your airflow system, and your gardening goals without creating unnecessary complexity.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Buy the tent around the bottleneck: light, height, airflow, humidity, access, or crop stage. The balanced system is the upgrade.
  </p>
</section>
